On Nov. 30 my son who has cerebral palsy was cashing his check at a bank in the Windsor Hills Shopping Center. He always goes to the same window and the teller helps him put his money into his wallet. As he was leaving a gentleman who had observed this transaction walked up to my son and said, &quot;Here's something for Christmas&quot; and handed him a $50 bill. Our son doesn't speak very well, but he did manage to thank the man. He was thrilled beyond belief and has recounted those few moments over and over to us.<br>
My husband and I want this gentleman to know how much his kindness and generosity has meant to our son. This &quot;random act of kindness&quot; indicates a wonderful Christmas spirit!<br>
Emogene G. Collins, Edmond<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That's from a letter to the editor out of the Daily Oklahoman. I keep telling myself to stop reading the paper because I can't afford the increased bloodpressure, but letters like this keep me coming back.<br>
Over the past 20 years I have read and seen and heard so many such stories about this place. I remember when I first came here what a striking contrast this city had with the places I had lived up north. Strangers walking down the street would actually ask in passing &quot;how ya doin?&quot; and then pause to listen if you would begin telling them. And I mean <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> listen</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. <br>
I've been at odds with my sister most of my life over the issue of birthdays and Christmas; she has always been of the opinion that the dollar sign on the sales slip for the present is more important than the connection between the giver and the recipient. I've always felt that the present should represent the message &quot;I care&quot;. And I don't mean &quot;here's something because you're on my christmas list&quot; but &quot;here's something you sighed at wistfully in passing in the mall 8 months ago&quot; or &quot;here's something that has to do with that stupid cartoon character you're always talking about&quot; or &quot;here's another ceramic E.T. doll to replace the one of mine you broke when we were arguing 7 years ago.&quot; or &quot;here's a batch of cookies, because I remembered, or asked around and found out, that you love home-baked treats but don't have anyone to make them for you anymore.&quot;  Or a $50 dollar bill to a stranger to say, &quot;I see how life can be tough for you, I care, and want you to have the means to get a little something extra for Christmas.&quot;<br>
<br>
God I love Oklahoma.<br>
