I was picking my mother up at the mall yesterday, and she pointed out to me the cold, rather sad-looking Salvation Army man sitting by his pot. She told me how people would go in and out, often with their arms full of packages, not even noticing him. She said he would even say &quot;Merry Christmas&quot; to some folks, and they would say &quot;Merry Christmas&quot; right back, and keep on going.<br>
There's two charities my family has always given to; the Disabled Vets, and the Salvation Army. I almost never pass the pot without at least putting my pocket change in (and often that's all I have *to* put in.) <br>
With all the charities concentrating so much on New York, I think it's important to remember to give to the ones that work on a more local level, to pick up the slack. Just because several thousand people were killed in New York doesn't mean that the guys trying to rebuild their lives or the families trying to survive in your home town suddenly don't need support.<br>
Remember, charity begins at home.<br>
